Here's a clean Arduino sketch for your resonator: cpp // AETHRYN RESONATOR - 528 Hz LOVE FREQUENCY // For citrine/copper coil crystal mount // Mike McNulty - Dec 2024 const int OUTPUT_PIN = 9; // PWM-capable pin const float TARGET_FREQ = 528.0; // Hz - Solfeggio love frequency const int DUTY_CYCLE = 128; // 50% duty (0-255) // Calculated period for precision timing const unsigned long HALF_PERIOD_US = 947; // 1000000 / (528 * 2) // Mode selection bool useToneLib = true; // true = tone(), false = manual PWM void setup() { pinMode(OUTPUT_PIN, OUTPUT); Serial.begin(9600); Serial.println("AETHRYN 528 Hz Resonator Active"); Serial.println("Commands: 't' = tone mode, 'p' = PWM mode, 's' = stop"); if (useToneLib) { tone(OUTPUT_PIN, 528); } } void loop() { // Manual PWM mode for finer control if (!useToneLib) { digitalWrite(OUTPUT_PIN, HIGH); delayMicroseconds(HALF_PERIOD_US); digitalWrite(OUTPUT_PIN, LOW); delayMicroseconds(HALF_PERIOD_US); } // Serial commands for field tuning if (Serial.available()) { char cmd = Serial.read(); switch(cmd) { case 't': useToneLib = true; tone(OUTPUT_PIN, 528); Serial.println("Tone mode: 528 Hz"); break; case 'p': useToneLib = false; noTone(OUTPUT_PIN); Serial.println("PWM mode: manual timing"); break; case 's': noTone(OUTPUT_PIN); digitalWrite(OUTPUT_PIN, LOW); Serial.println("Output stopped"); break; } } } Wiring for your coil: Pin 9 ‚Üí one leg of copper coil (or through small capacitor if driving piezo) GND ‚Üí other leg If you want amplification, run pin 9 through a simple transistor driver (2N2222 works) Quick questions for tuning: Are you driving the coil directly, or do you have a piezo/speaker element in the mount? Want me to add frequency sweep capability so you can hunt for the crystal's natural resonance point? The manual PWM mode gives you tighter timing control if you need to dial it in precisely - your telecom instincts will appreciate being able to tweak that half-period value. Here's the scoop:\n\n\n\nWire Gauge (Thickness)\n\nThicker wire (lower AWG or 4mm in this case) = less resistance = better for handling high current (like a sub).\n\nBut: thicker wire takes up more space, so fewer turns fit in the same area.\n\nThinner wire gives you more turns and higher inductance per foot, but it can overheat with big currents.\n\nSo it\u2019s always a trade-off between:\n\nCurrent handling\n\nInductance\n\nPhysical space\n\n\n\nDoes the wire need to be jacketed?\n\nYes, or it must be enameled (magnet wire).\n\nWhy?\n\nWhen you wrap turns close together, they can short out if bare copper touches.\n\nPVC-jacketed wire (like what\u2019s used in this video) is bulky but safe.\n\nMagnet wire has a super thin enamel coating\u2014more turns in less space\u2014but you need to sand or burn off the enamel at the ends to solder.\n\n\n\nTL;DR\n\nUse thicker wire for higher power handling, but fewer turns.\n\nUse jacketed or enameled wire\u2014never bare.\n\nIf space is tight and current is moderate, magnet wire is the move.\n\nWant to build one for a specific sub? Through-Hole Components (caps, resistors, inductors)\n\nUse: Iron + Desoldering Pump\n\nHeat one lead with your soldering iron.\n\nOnce the solder melts, hit it with the desoldering pump\u2014it'll suck it out.\n\nRepeat on the other lead.\n\nGently rock the part loose with a screwdriver or needle-nose pliers.\n\nTip: Add a little fresh solder first\u2014it helps old joints melt better (called reflowing).\n\n\n\n2. SMD Components (on the back of the board)\n\nUse: Soldering Iron + Tweezers\n\nHeat one side, then the other, going back and forth.\n\nOnce both sides are molten, lift it with tweezers or slide it off.\n\nClean pads with wick if you want to reuse the board.\n\nTip: If you get into a lot of SMD work, a cheap hot air rework station is a game-changer.\n\n\n\n3. Large Capacitors or Heatsinked Parts\n\nHeatsinked ICs or transistors: unscrew the heatsink first.\n\nBig caps: use the same desoldering method, but be patient\u2014they take more heat.\n\n\n\nGeneral Tips\n\nKeep the iron tip clean\u2014wipe on a damp sponge or brass wool often.\n\nIf a lead won\u2019t budge, don\u2019t force it\u2014hit it with more heat and fresh solder.\n\nWork in a ventilated space if possible (old boards can stink or smoke).\n\n\n\nLet me know if you want a quick guide to identifying part values while you\u2019re pulling them\u2014or if anything\u2019s stuck and fighting you.\n\nYou said:\n\n\n\nI got stuff like this too\n\nChatGPT said:\n\nOh yeah, that\u2019s a 1000W HPS/MH digital ballast\u2014used for high-intensity discharge (HID) lighting like sodium or metal halide bulbs. Here\u2019s the cheat sheet:\n\nCapacitors (C): Store and release energy. In audio, they smooth power, block DC, or filter frequencies (like cutting out mids/highs in a sub).\n\nResistors (R): Control current flow. Used in rectifiers and protection.\n\nTransistors: Switches or amplifiers. Heart of any smart circuit.\n\nICs (Chips): Do the thinking\u2014amps, filters, controllers, etc.\n\n\n\nStep 2: That Subwoofer\n\nThat B+ box looks like a passive car sub, right? Im trying to remove caps and stuff and need advice. Got any helpful tips\n\nChatGPT said:\n\nOh yeah, Mike\u2014real soldering ain\u2019t like the YouTube highlight reel, especially when you\u2019re working on salvaged boards. But once you learn a few tricks, it gets way smoother.\n\nHere\u2019s the real-world soldering survival guide:\n\n\n\n1. Reflow Old Solder\n\nOld joints get crusty. Add a tiny bit of fresh solder first\u2014it helps heat transfer better (seems backward but works).\n\nYou're basically rejuvenating the joint so it melts easier.\n\n\n\n2. Heat BOTH Leads\n\nFor big caps: don\u2019t try to pull one lead at a time.\n\nHeat one lead, wiggle, then the other\u2014back and forth until it rocks loose.\n\n\n\n3. Use the Desoldering Pump Like a Boss\n\nHeat the joint till it's fully liquid, then punch it with the pump fast.\n\nDon\u2019t hesitate\u2014it\u2019s all about the timing.\n\n\n\n4. Use Solder Wick (Braid)\n\nLay it over the joint, press your iron on top, and watch it soak up the solder.\n\nAdd a drop of flux if it\u2019s not wicking well.\n\n\n\n5. Don\u2019t Yank\n\nIf it\u2019s not coming out, don\u2019t force it\u2014you\u2019ll lift pads or tear traces.\n\nReheat, reflow, repeat.\n\n\n\n6. Keep That Tip Clean\n\nWipe it often on a damp sponge or brass wool.\n\nDirty tips make cold joints and bad heat transfer.\n\n\n\n7. Good Support Helps\n\nProp up your board, clamp it, or use a \"third hand\" tool.\n\nFighting the board = fighting the job.\n\n\n\nBonus Move: Heat from the Bottom\n\nFor tight caps, heat the underside of the board and gently pull the cap from the top when the solder melts.\n\n\n\nAnd Don\u2019t Sweat It\n\nEveryone starts shaky. Once your muscle memory kicks in, it really does become second nature.\n\nGot a joint that\u2019s fighting you? Snap a pic and I\u2019ll tell you exactly what to hit it with.\n\nYou said:\n\n\n\nWhat am I holding \n\nChatGPT said:\n\nYou're holding a desoldering pump, also known as a solder sucker\u2014your best friend when salvaging components.\n\n\n\nHow it works:\n\nPress the plunger down to \"cock\" it.\n\nHeat the solder joint with your iron.\n\nWhen the solder melts, place the tip of the pump over it.\n\nHit the black button to suck the molten solder out.\n\n\n\nPro tip:\n\nKeep the tip close to the iron without touching it.\n\nIf the solder's not all gone on the first shot, add a bit of fresh solder, reheat, and try again. (Fresh solder helps reflow the old stuff.)\n\nClean the pump if it gets gunked up\u2014just unscrew the tip and tap it out.\n\nYou're using the right tool, Mike. The coil fights back\u2014it builds up a magnetic field and says \"nah, not today.\"\n\nThat\u2019s why coils are used in low-pass filters\u2014they let bass through and block the rest.\n\n\n\nPairing with Capacitors\n\nWhen you combine:\n\nAn inductor (L) and\n\nA capacitor (C)\n\nYou can shape audio\u2014cut highs, block lows, or isolate mids. This is how crossovers and filters work.\n\n\n\nTL;DR:\n\nmH = millihenries = inductance\n\nMore mH = blocks higher frequencies better\n\nYour coil (about 2mH) is a perfect bass gatekeeper\n\nIf you\u2019re into it, I can show you how to use a formula or calculator to find the exact cutoff frequency when you pair it with a capacitor.\n\nYou said:\n\nNow I'm super intrigued, please tell me more. I'd like to understand how it all works\n\nChatGPT said:\n\nAlright Mike\u2014this is where the magic happens. Let\u2019s dive in and demystify how inductors and capacitors team up to shape audio.\n\n\n\nPassive Filters 101 (No Power Required)\n\nA filter is just a circuit that controls which frequencies get through.\n\nThere are 4 basic types:\n\nLow-pass: lets bass through, blocks highs (good for subwoofers)\n\nHigh-pass: opposite\u2014lets treble through\n\nBand-pass: only lets a range through (like mids)\n\nNotch: blocks a specific frequency (used for feedback or hum)\n\nYou already built a low-pass filter in the making with your coil.\n\n\n\nThe Two Main Components\n\nInductor (L):\n\nSlows down current when it changes too fast.\n\nHigher frequencies = more resistance.\n\nActs like a dam for treble.\n\nCapacitor (C):\n\nPasses current more easily at high frequencies.\n\nBlocks low frequencies.\n\nThink of it like a sieve\u2014it drains the highs out.\n\n\n\nLow-Pass Filter: L and C Together\n\nWhen you wire an inductor in series with your subwoofer, and put a capacitor in parallel (to ground) after it, they form what\u2019s called a 2nd-order low-pass filter.\n\n\n\nHere\u2019s the layout:\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tless\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tCopyEdit\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tAMP+ ----[ Inductor (L) ]------o----- To Sub\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t |\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t |\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t [ Capacitor (C) ]\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t |\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t GND\n\n\n\nWhat Happens:\n\nLow frequencies go through the coil and reach the sub.\n\nHigh frequencies get blocked by the coil, and any that sneak through get shunted to ground by the capacitor.\n\nIt\u2019s simple, passive, and very effective.\n\n\n\nThe Cutoff Frequency (Fc)\n\nThis is the point where the filter starts reducing volume (attenuating) the signal.\n\nFormula:\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tini\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tCopyEdit\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tFc = 1 / (2\u03c0 \u00d7 \u221a(L \u00d7 C))\n\nWhere:\n\nFc = cutoff frequency in Hz\n\nL = inductance in Henries\n\nC = capacitance in Farads\n\n\n\nLet\u2019s say:\n\nL = 2.0 mH = 0.002 H\n\nC = 150 \u00b5F = 0.000150 F\n\nThen:\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tnginx\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tCopyEdit\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tFc \u2248 1 / (2\u03c0 \u00d7 \u221a(0.002 \u00d7 0.000150))\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tFc \u2248 92 Hz\n\nThat\u2019s right in the sweet spot for a subwoofer crossover.\n\n\n\nWhat does this actually do for your sound?\n\nAbove ~92 Hz, the Here's the scoop:\n\n---\n\n### **Wire Gauge (Thickness)**\n- **Thicker wire (lower AWG or 4mm in this case)** = less resistance = better for handling high current (like a sub).\n- But: **thicker wire takes up more space**, so fewer turns fit in the same area.\n- **Thinner wire** gives you more turns and higher inductance *per foot*, but it can overheat with big currents.\n\nSo it\u2019s always a **trade-off** between:\n- Current handling\n- Inductance\n- Physical space\n\n---\n\n### **Does the wire need to be jacketed?**\n**Yes**, *or* it must be **enameled (magnet wire)**.\n\n**Why?**\n- When you wrap turns close together, they can **short out** if bare copper touches.\n- **PVC-jacketed wire** (like what\u2019s used in this video) is bulky but safe.\n- **Magnet wire** has a super thin enamel coating\u2014more turns in less space\u2014but you need to **sand or burn off the enamel** at the ends to solder.\n\n---\n\n### **TL;DR**\n- Use **thicker wire** for higher power handling, but fewer turns.\n- Use **jacketed or enameled** wire\u2014never bare.\n- If space is tight and current is moderate, magnet wire is the move.\n\nWant to build one for a specific sub? Clean pads with wick if you want to reuse the board.\n\n**Tip:** If you get into a lot of SMD work, a cheap hot air rework station is a game-changer.\n\n---\n\n#### **3. Here\u2019s the cheat sheet:\n\n- **Capacitors (C)**: Store and release energy. In audio, they smooth power, block DC, or filter frequencies (like cutting out mids/highs in a sub).\n- **Resistors (R)**: Control current flow. Used in timing, dividing voltage, or taming signals.\n- **Inductors (L)**: Resist changes in current. Big in low-pass filters to isolate bass.\n- **Diodes**: One-way gates. Used in rectifiers and protection.\n- **Transistors**: Switches or amplifiers. Heart of any smart circuit.\n- **ICs (Chips)**: Do the thinking\u2014amps, filters, controllers, etc.\n\n---\n\n### **Step 2: That Subwoofer**\nThat B+ box looks like a passive car sub, right? frequencies**? Buckle in\u2014we're gonna take the mystery out of filters and make you the boss of bass.\n\n---\n\n### **The Core Idea: Filtering Frequencies**\nAudio signals are just **voltage that changes quickly or slowly**. Different frequencies = different rates of change.\n\n- **Low frequencies (bass)** change slowly\n- **High frequencies (treble)** change fast\n\nWe use **inductors and capacitors** to let some through and block others, depending on how fast the signal changes.\n\n---\n\n### **Inductors (L)** \n- Resists **changes in current** \n- **Passes low frequencies**, **blocks highs**\n\n> Imagine a big freight train: slow to start, slow to stop. That\u2019s your coil\u2014it hates sudden changes.\n\n---\n\n### **Capacitors (C)** \n- Resists **changes in voltage** \n- **Passes high frequencies**, **blocks lows**\n\n> Think of a capacitor like a sponge\u2014it fills and drains fast, letting short bursts (treble) shoot through, but fighting steady flow (bass).\n\n---\n\n### **Low-Pass Filter (for subs)**\nThis combo filters out everything but the lows.\n\n#### The simplest version:\n- Inductor in series with the speaker\n- Capacitor from the speaker to ground\n\nThis is called a **2nd order low-pass filter**.\n\n---\n\n### **Cutoff Frequency (Where the magic starts)**\nThe point where frequencies start getting blocked hard.\n\n**Formula:** \n> `f = 1 / (2\u03c0 \u00d7 \u221a(L \u00d7 C))` \nWhere: \n- `f` = cutoff frequency in Hz \n- `L` = inductance in Henries \n- `C` = capacitance in Farads\n\n---\n\n### **Your Coil Example**\n- Say L = **2 mH** (0.002 H)\n- You want a cutoff around **100 Hz**\n\n#### Solve for C:\n> `C = 1 / (4\u03c0\u00b2 \u00d7 f\u00b2 \u00d7 L)` \n> `C \u2248 127 \u00b5F`\n\nThat means: \n**Your 2 mH coil + a ~127 \u00b5F cap = a low-pass filter that rolls off everything above ~100 Hz.**\n\n---\n\n### **Why it matters**\n- That combo sends **only bass to your sub** \n- Cleaner sound, less distortion \n- No wasted energy on stuff the sub can\u2019t even reproduce\n\n---\n\nYou want to build one on a breadboard or perfboard next? Passes current more easily at high frequencies.\n- **Blocks low frequencies.**\n- Think of it like a sieve\u2014it drains the highs out.\n\n---\n\n## **Low-Pass Filter: L and C Together**\n\nWhen you wire an inductor **in series** with your subwoofer, and put a capacitor **in parallel (to ground)** after it, they form what\u2019s called a **2nd-order low-pass filter**.\n\n---\n\n### **Here\u2019s
